Do you know how you can protect your self from some snake bites if your stung and far away from a hospital? Electricity. Add electricity to the bite. I heard of a guy that was out in the middle of no where, some where, and all that he had was his car. He took out his spark plugs right away, and with the car running, and wires connected to the spark plug he put it on the bite. And it felt terrible, but he made it home.  From what I understand snake poison is basically proteins that your body can not absorb, and the electricity will straighten them out, and make them absorb able. If people ever wondered why there is this symbol with the snakes on a pole, on ambulances and other medical vehicles or buildings or books, its because in the original creation they were made for healing. Snakes see with infrared...which is to say they see heat. And if your hurt, usually it will be hotter there, because your blood is rushing there to heal things. The narrator on this video is overly dramatic -- you will NOT necessarily "lose your leg" if you are stung by a stone-fish, there is an anti-venom, but the pain is serious may require hospitalization, depending on how much venom was injected.  If you are in an area where this fish can be found, wear tennis shoes to wade and swim, and DON'T ever pick up ANY sea creature, unless you are completely knowledgeable about the animal and know how to handle it.  Many animals will act defensively, and react with whatever they're capable of, and that can be harmful.
You don't have to "run away as fast as you can and ask for help" if you leave most creatures alone!   They are NOT out to get you (with the exception of a couple of aggressive snakes, not in North America,  which will chase you) or most animals who are territorial and protecting their young, but most flying insects won't bother you except for flies and mosquitoes, wasps, hornets gnats, etc., but stinging insects like bees, may attack you  if you're near their nests or handle them, but handling some ground bugs can cause irritation -- best to just leave all of them them alone.  They're part of what makes our ecosystems function!
That catipillar isn't as dangerous as you think, watch coyote peterson's video. The pain is mild, for example it feels like being stung by a red ant. And you shouldn't go run and ask for help for a harmless creature. This "Bright Side" channel wasn't accurately named. After all this video shows how not so bright it is.

"Run Fast and Ask for Help!" No, some of these can simply be ignored. Just because it's unsafe to tamper with doesn't mean it poses imminent danger. A caterpillar isn't going to chase you down and attack you, for example, so if you see it, leave it alone. Nor is a scorpion going to be able to catch you if you walk away. You don't need to run, and you certainly don't need to waste other people's time freaking out and trying to "get help" because you saw one.

South America Fortunately, it is very rare to find Brazilian wandering spiders in the UK or anywhere outside their natural habitat in South America. They live in the forests of Costa Rica, Columbia, Peru, Brazil, and Paraguay and gain their name from the habit of moving across jungle floors at night in search of food      Africa For these reasons, the black mamba is widely considered the world's deadliest snake. Black mambas live in the savannas and rocky hills of southern and eastern Africa. They are Africa's longest venomous snake, reaching up to 14 feet in length, although 8.2 feet is more the average.

Wikipedia:  Cone snail venoms are mainly peptides. The venoms contain many different toxins that vary in their effects; some are extremely toxic. The sting of small cones is no worse than a bee sting, but the sting of a few of the larger species of tropical cone snails can be serious, occasionally even fatal to humans. worst click bait, all hype, no helpful info, where do these creatures live, info is bad and some of it is plain wrong, i.e. the box jellyfish the # killer is very misleading.  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_jellyfish Taxonomy and systematics "Box jellyfish" and "sea wasp" are common names for the highly venomous Chironex fleckeri.[1] However, these terms are ambiguous, as "sea wasp" and "marine stinger" are sometimes used to refer to other jellyfish.[citation needed]  At least 51 species of box jellyfish were known as of 2018.[2] These are grouped into two orders and eight families.[3] A few new species have since been described, and it is likely that additional undescribed species remain.[4][5][6]

As an Australian living on the beach - the box jellyfish isn't the most deadly jellyfish. In fact if you immediately treat the sting and get to the hospital you'll usually be fine. The real problem is the irukandji. They're a close relative of the box jellyfish that grows to only about 1cm (2-3cm stingers) and is almost completely invisible. They're the most deadly subspecies of 'box jellyfish' and a huge proportion of stings end in death. From almost certain death for children and elderly, and still a decent chance of death for healthy adults.  Also yeah cone snails are terrifying. Starting with your first, highly puzzling suggestion: Why would I "RUN" - let alone "RUN FAST?"  I mean, these things couldn't possibly even begin to approach, let alone match my slowest walking speed...and it's not like they can fly, or jump onto me.  Instead, I'd rather stick around to watch something that is this strange and beautiful for a while, and see what it would do.  Specifically, I'd be most interested to observe its ambulation (fast, slow, undulating, smooth etc.) and other characteristics or habits, like eating, mating, fighting etc..  Then, after seeing all I wanted (or just getting bored), I'd amble away to continue doing whatever I was engaged in prior to spotting the cute, little yella' fella'.  Moving on to your second moronic suggestion: ("Ask for Help!"), I'll respond with a question: Why?  I wouldn't need any help to watch it.   Finally, my thoughts about what your above suggestion might mean/from where they stem: Considering the highly obtuse nature of your advice when encountering this type of insect, I would suggest that the name you chose for your channel - "BRIGHT SIDE" - cannot possibly bear any relation to your level of intellect.  As such, I would suggest that the name "DIM Side" (as in 'dim wit' or 'dim bulb') would be a much more accurate picture of your true cognitive abilities and level of intelligence.  It's either that, or you are 1) suffering from entomophobia, 2) extremely cowardly or 3) BOTH.    For any or all of the above, strongly urge you to seek the services of a professional.  In other words, take YOUR OWN ADVICE.  I'm referring to the advice you gave to all viewers when they read the title of your video: "...Run Fast and Ask for Help!"  (Actually, it would be easier if - instead of doing the "RUN" thing, you just Googled "mental health professionals in your area," then placed a call to one located fairly near to you and scheduled an appointment.)    BTW: You're welcome.  Good luck with the therapy!

Yayy Komodo Dragon is Number 2 and ITS from Indonesia
Stonefish aren't just in the ocean. Here in Australia, they are in small creeks and the larger rivers. Even the smaller creeks in the hinterland areas without any ocean nearby. I've heard people say they only sit in the ocean or warmer environments, which is untrue. Some videos have said they don't live in Australia. Which is a lie. I've seen them firsthand, and even NationalGEO had an episode on (Seconds to disaster) (or a show like it) where an Aussie on the Sunshine Coast, QLD was stung. It is a huge threat to a lot of local swimmers throughout Australia, and I'm sure other countries.  Blue-ringed Octopus and Box Jellyfish are insanely common along the north eastern side of Australia (Guess who's speaking from experience :P ). So if you're planning a trip to Bondi Beach...just be aware...four of these threats reside there (stonefish, black mamba, jellyfish and the BROctopus)

And the worst thing about Box Jellies is they are very SMALL and very difficult to see. Fortunately, the are found only around Austrailia so stay away from down undah. And the mortality rates of their stings in this video is GREATLY overstated. Not many people die, however, the victims my be in excruciating pain for up to 48 or more hours, probably WISHING they were dead.

People always seem to get poison and venom mixed up. Poison is deadly when absorbed or ingested. Venom on the other hand is always injected. Venom is generally not toxic if swallowed, unless you have an open wound somewhere inside you to introduce it to your blood stream.

Being stung by a cone snail is not necessarily a death sentence. True there is no antivenom or cure, however the severity of the sting depends on the area you are stung in and the amount of venom injected. If you get to a hospital early enough they will be able to save your life. Performing CPR on the victim can also save their life.

That's actually not how Komodo Dragons hunt. They have saliva that contains deadly bacteria that rots flesh in less than a 24 hour period. They bite their prey mostly in the leg as they tend to go after water buffalo and then they follow it, stalking it for days until the animal succoms to infection and can no longer fight them off. Say it with me people: VENOM!!! Many people including parts of this video mix up poison and venom. Poison is INGESTED, meaning you have to eat it or get it into your digestive system for it to work. Venom is INJECTED (most of the time) meaning an organism must jab you or bite you and pump venom into you. Also, some vocab words for everyone: -hemotoxin: toxins that affect your blood, causing it to not be able to clot or makes you bleed internally -neurotoxin: this toxin binds with your synapses to delay or stop brain signals from firing or being received, eventually shutting down vital body organs and functions such as your heart pumping or your lungs breathing -cytotoxin: affects body cells, causing them to do a variety of weird things

Only use vinegar to get the jelly fish or the rest of the tentacles that have fallen off of the jelly fish that are still on your leg off but not too much because it makes the venom spread more quickly.  It's important that you do this quickly because the longer the tentacles are on there, the more venom you get injected into yourself. Next, always make sure you are with somebody because if you aren't, then you are absolutely dead. If you are, you have a much better chance of living than death. Before we get to possible ways of saving you (basically the only way) here is what the poison does to you. It's stops your brain from working properly so you will soon be unable to see, and you can't breathe. With a few seconds, you will be unconscious, and your heart will stop beating. I'm truly sorry if I am scaring you, but this is true. Next, the person or people you are with must work together, even out of fear of losing their friend, to save you. If you are with one person, they must perform CPR immediately after you go unconscious, and scream for help.They must continue to perform CPR until they get you to the nearest hospital. If you are with more than one person (lets say you're with like ten friends for a summer vacation party at the beach), have two to three people (more if it's really bad and people have to change for the CPR due to arms getting tired and running out of breath), and the others must go and find as much help as possible. When you get to the hospital, they with use the defibrillator to get your heart to start beating again. It wont be the hospital that will have saved you. It will be your friends and other people the performed CPR and your friends and the other people that help you get as much as help as possible.

Ok, this list is jacked up.  The main problem is the box jellyfish.  First off, most the box jellyfish youll find in say the waters of florida are Chiropsella bart which only leave itchiny and mild pain, and what looks like string burn marks on you.  The deadliest box jelly fish Chironex fleckeri is mostly found in australia and has only been linked to 64 deaths between now and 1983.    So really, no, the box jellyfish doesnt even get close to topping this list. The snakes are not listed in the right order. And the cone snail is not instant death. Only 36 people in the past 90 years have died.  The facts about the animals on this list are also very wrong.

Your info on komodo dragons is either incorrect or out of date.  Komodo dragons don't generally rush an animal and tear out their throat.  They bit the animal, even in a peripheral area (such as on a leg), and then they track the animal as it quickly dies from aggressive infection, from the ridiculous amount of bacteria in the dragon's mouth.  There is debate now over whether komodo dragon's use just bacteria or if they're really venomous.

You managed to completely miss the thing that makes a komodo dragon deadly. Namely, the horde of bacteria living in their mouth. When a komodo dragon bites its prey, saliva full of the bacteria seeps into the wound. If the prey escapes, or is allowed to escape, it will eventually succumb to blood poisoning from the bacteria. The Komodo dragon (or dragons, in some cases) will stalk the prey until it collapses, either dead or too weak to resist, and then feed. You make it sound like, if they can't reach your throat, you're fine.

Box jellyfish are the most dangerous animal in the world for several reasons. It's venom is very effective, first of all, and kills very quickly. Other reasons are it small and nearly transparent in the water which makes spotting them nearly impossible.  In australia, certain  beaches are so overrun with box jellyfish during the summer months that they have to net swimming areas off to keep the jellyfish away from swimmers. Going outside the netted areas will most certainly get you stung and no one will be able to come to save you due to the risk of getting stung themselves.

Please stop saying poison. Animals are VENOMOUS not POISONOUS. Venom and poison are very different things.   Venom is a protein created by animals in specific glands. You CAN ingest all venoms (assuming you dont have any internal cuts or sores) and digest them safely.  Poison is pretty much anything you CANT ingest and digest safely.

You thing that I would point out is the misconception abour Brazilian Wandering Spiders.  There is a similar looking species that is often mistaken for the Wandering Spider, and the look alike spider lives in banana trees and is often brought home even in the US but it is not dangerous.  The true Wandering Spider lives on the floor of rain forests and does not build a web so it walks around thus the name.  Wandering Spiders seldom come into contact with people and do not live in houses.  When they are threatened they raise up their front legs in a menacing manner.

I don't mean to be that one smartass that everyone hates, but poison dart frogs are only venomous because of their diet. They eat a certain cricket that causes their body to produce a type of poison that is very deadly to humans and many other creatures. This cricket is also eaten by the pitohui, like the poison dart frog this bird has toxins, but the toxins are in the feathers of the bird, but are not as deadly. And during the breeding season (mostly at start of springs )there are thousands of them here and there. And you can find them anywhere and mistakenly stung by them. Result is really bad. *The socalled "Africanized" honeybees were NOT "genetically engineered", that is nonsense. They were bred the normal old way.* And while it was an experiment, it was not done by a random "Brazillian man", it was done by biologists and apiarists (beekepeers) in an attempt to acclimatise European honeybees (which are a domesticated species) to hot tropical climates and parasites that they were dying from and to increase honey yields, by breeding them with queens of African wild bee species. This hybridization breeding did succeed, in a way: the hybrid bees thrived and fought off parasites and attackers vigorously. The problem now was, they became hard for beekeepers to handle because they were way more aggressive than the domesticated European honeybee. Yields went down instead of up because African wild bees live in smaller colonies that don't collect as much honey (because they don't have to store honey for the long European winter), they are more nomadic and the entire colony may leave their hive when disturbed (by beekeepers trying to harvest the honey, for example), and colonies create more young queens and split up far more often per year than European honeybees, making it more difficult for beekeepers to keep an eye on them. European honeybees build large hives, because they have to store enough food for the winter, but building a large hive means more time and work, meaning the bees have more incentive to stay put and less incentive to leave their precious hive at a moment's notice. European bees were domesticated and breed over millenia to be tame and docile, too. The African bees used in the hybridization breeding were not. You can still handle them, if you know how to do it (very carefully).

I would like to add something to the conversation about the cone snails in this video. There are several different types of cone snails all resting under the genus _Conus._ Cone snails have venom of varying levels of toxicity and risk to humans. The snail referred to in this list is specifically _Conus geographus,_ or the geographic cone snail, which is native to the reefs of the Indo-Pacific. The reason their venom is so potent is actually quite interesting! They need a quick and effective tool to incapacitate speedy fish, which make up their diet.

When you said victims of the deathstalker did you mean fatalities or just getting stung. Because I find it incredibly hard to believe that more people get stung by that thing and not the bark scorpion.   In case you don't know, bark scorpions can climb on vertical walls (and on rare occasion on your ceiling) and they like small spaces. They are also flat enough that it is incredibly difficult to keep them out of your house, and can easily crawl through most doors. Once they get inside, their fondess of small spaces mean they are very likely to hide somewhere like underneath clothes left on the floor, or in your shoe. They of course hide in many non-clothing related items(for example, I left my gameboy on a couch once and when I picked it up there was a bark scorpion on the bottom), but these are common examples of how people get stung. Oh, and they are also very high up on the list of scorpions you don't want to get stung by.

The bees are "genetically engineered"... Africanized honey bees as you call them are just a hybrid between the gentler european honeybee (usually lingusticus or ibriensis) and the african honeybee (scutellata). Never was there anything 'genetically engineered'.  They just cross breeded them because the african bee acts on the varroa mite by biting them to death and the european doesn't but is gentler and easier to handle.

For anyone curious about location:  (13) - Asp Caterpillar = Eastern USA (Virginia through Florida) and Southern USA into Mexico and Central America 12 - Deathstalker Scorpion = Arid areas in Middle East, North America and Northern/Central Africa 11 - Carpet Viper = Northern/Central Africa, across the Middle east into the Indian subcontinent 10 - Cone Snail = Pacific and Indian ocean, as well as the Caribbean sea in the Atlantic; as far west as Florida --> side note: these snails aren't aggressive and almost always only sting when threatened so just don't pick them up and you'll be fine... no running required 9 - Stone Fish = Coastal Northern Australia 8 - Africanized Honey Bee = Originally Brazil --> now as far south as Argentina and as far north as Florida and southern California 7 - Brazilian Wandering Spider = Across South America (especially around the equator) and Central America --> These spiders are also called 'Banana Spiders' because they can travel on banana shipments, and have been found in supermarkets around the world. 6 - Black Mamba = Southern and Eastern Africa 5 - Poison Dart Frog = South America (especially around the equator) and Central America (Panama/Nicaragua) 4 - Tsetse = sub-Saharan Africa 3 - Blue ringed octopus = Indo-Pacific region (as far west as Madagascar, as far east as Solomon islands, as far south as Southern Australia and as far north as Southern Japan) 2 - Komodo Dragon = Localised to the Indonesian archipelago  1 - Box Jellyfish = Indo-Pacific region (From Northern Australia to the Phillipines --> can reach southern Japan and almost as far east as New Zealand)

Lost me at number 12. Cannibalism is a completely normal behavior among a wide variety of animals, it's just the way their ecology works, they're not "evil". Comparing animal behavior (particularly invertebrates) with behavior we consider "wrong" or extreme in human life is just ignoring the diversity of nature. There's no reason to spread fearful responses to any kind of animal, if you don't know what it is, simply leave it alone and observe from a safe distance. Learn from them.

Irukanji jellyfish is far more toxic and dangerous than the box jellyfish,  in regards to snakes the Inland Taipan is the world's most dangerous and toxic snake.  Both of those nasty critters are very common here in Australia.  The Irukanji jellyfish is very tiny average size I've seen is no bigger than a box of matches.  The inland taipan is a very aggressive snake,  bad tempered and will attack,  they also grow up to 8 ft in length,  I've killed a few that came into my yard when I lived in far north Queensland years ago.

This is the drumbeat video I've ever seen.   Also, I'm a beekeeper in TX. I've extensively studied bees and there is absolutely no evidence of something referred to as an "Africanized Honey Bee". In fact all bees originated from Africa, there's no genetic difference and no way to test for "killer bees" environment makes all the difference, a docile hive can turn super aggressive if they've been exposed and they feel the hive is threatened. Bees that build low have to fend off rodents and other pests/predators and will always be more aggressive. Get into a hive when it's too cold and don't expect them to take the threat to their warm winter home to be taken lightly.

2:28:  A weak aspect of this video is the fact that the creators have neglected to talk about WHERE these animals exist, and when one might encounter them. For example an animal that hibernates in winter is less liable to pose a threat during that season. This information can easily come across as crass fearmongering when it excludes the most basic information.

The bright colors thing is only half true. In Tennessee we have Garden Spiders that are large (Usually a sign it's not a venomous spider.) and they have mostly vibrant white like a skeleton yet have a little dollop of bright green or yellow. Design Tip: Use light/dark contrast as well as color contrast. White on bright red, orange, the further you go toward yellow, gets harder and harder to see. A darker red background with bold white type would've given the text a lot more pop. It may seem like the bright red would be the best, but even a little bit darker red helps it a lot. Traditionally, they used about 10% black added to bright red or bright cyan for the spot red and spot "blue," while reflex blue is basically royal blue, about 100% cyan and !00% magenta.

I think you meant the irukandji jellyfish. Though box jellyfishes are deadly, irukandji are MUCH deadlier. They live in the same place as box jellyfish too. They are much smaller so are hard to notice, but what really makes the, dangerous is unlike box jellyfish stings which give instant and immensive pain and large whip-lash-looking stung areas, irukandji rather leave an incredibly small area of very small baubles on your skin that has no inflammation, they just look like goosebumps. That's especially why they're so deadly; no-one notices they've been stung. You just get incredibly sick and begin a slow, painful decent to death.
